34:36.367 --> 34:37.266
It's not like that.

34:37.300 --> 34:38.900
- The only thing
that doesn't piss you off.

34:38.934 --> 34:41.400
[laughter]

34:41.433 --> 34:44.400
- That's funny.
That's funny.

34:44.433 --> 34:45.667
Connor T. texted,

34:45.700 --> 34:49.133
"Ashton, did you even
consider Adrian competition

34:49.166 --> 34:53.633
"when it came to the two of you
pursuing Laura?"

34:53.667 --> 34:56.133
[laughing]

34:56.166 --> 34:57.500
- You can never
count somebody out.

34:57.533 --> 34:59.967
Um, but, I mean, it's fair game.

35:00.000 --> 35:01.367
You know,
as Adrian was saying,

35:01.400 --> 35:03.567
we had a-we actually had
a very good relationship,
him and I,

35:03.600 --> 35:05.333
as we were very honest
with each other.

35:05.367 --> 35:07.266
And we established that
from the beginning.

35:07.300 --> 35:09.066
Is we had just an open line
between us.

35:09.100 --> 35:10.600
- How does Laura feel
about that?

35:10.633 --> 35:13.367
- Fair game.
I don't--

35:13.400 --> 35:15.767
- Well, in-in early stages,
it is fair game.

35:15.800 --> 35:17.567
- Fair game?
- Of course.

35:17.600 --> 35:19.533
I had no claim on Laura from
when she got on to the boat.

35:19.567 --> 35:20.533
- Is this "Hunger Games?"

35:20.567 --> 35:22.667
Like, kind of.
Kind of.

35:22.700 --> 35:27.133
- The, uh--
Your terminology is amazing.
- Yeah.

35:27.166 --> 35:29.033
- I think he meant
dating is fair game.

35:29.066 --> 35:30.567
Not Laura, specifically.
- Yeah.

35:30.600 --> 35:31.800
- Yeah, yeah.
Exactly, yeah.

35:31.834 --> 35:32.800
- Right.
Okay.

35:32.834 --> 35:35.667
Adrian, are you still
in an open relationship?

35:35.700 --> 35:36.633
- No.
- No.

35:36.667 --> 35:39.400
- I'm currently single.

35:39.433 --> 35:42.867
- Coming up...
I have a surprise for you guys.

35:42.900 --> 35:46.200
Please welcome the cameraman
who saved Ashton.

35:46.233 --> 35:48.300
♪♪♪

35:53.433 --> 35:53.867
- We're gonna talk about

35:53.867 --> 35:54.166
- We're gonna talk about
Ashton's accident

35:55.033 --> 35:56.633
in just a minute,
but I wanna go around

35:56.667 --> 35:59.300
and find out what your biggest
regret of the season is,

35:59.333 --> 36:01.400
and what you're doing now.
Adrian.

36:01.433 --> 36:03.667
- Um, my biggest regret is
probably not being more mindful

36:03.700 --> 36:05.633
of my coworkers'
feelings at times.

36:05.667 --> 36:07.500
And now I'm working in New York.

36:07.533 --> 36:09.467
I'm working for
a private couple.

36:09.500 --> 36:11.467
- Tyler.
- No regrets.

36:11.500 --> 36:15.000
Had a blast.
And I'm living in New Orleans.

36:15.033 --> 36:15.767
- Rhylee.

36:15.800 --> 36:17.200
- Um, obviously,
my biggest regret

36:17.233 --> 36:23.633
is-is how I spoke to superiors.
Um, and right now,

36:23.667 --> 36:25.900
I've been working on
a couple different boats.

36:25.934 --> 36:28.333
- Um, probably my biggest regret
was the way that

36:28.367 --> 36:30.633
I handled Caroline's exit.

36:30.667 --> 36:32.500
Should have handled it
in a different way.

36:32.533 --> 36:34.567
And, um, I'm currently living
between Majorca, Spain,

36:34.600 --> 36:37.100
and Manchester as well.
- Kate.

36:37.133 --> 36:40.200
- Yeah, my biggest regret
is the childish way

36:40.233 --> 36:44.567
that I acted with Caroline.
Um, was not great to watch.

36:44.600 --> 36:45.633
And-- oh.

36:45.667 --> 36:47.467
I opened up a non-profit store
in my hometown

36:47.500 --> 36:49.700
about a year and a half ago.
- Laura.

36:49.734 --> 36:51.834
- My biggest regret
would definitely be, um,

36:51.867 --> 36:54.266
not hand-handling the situation
as I did with Kate.

36:54.300 --> 36:57.300
I should have, you know,
sat her down
like a professional.

36:57.333 --> 36:58.633
And, right now,
I'm living in Toronto,

36:58.667 --> 37:00.700
and I'm a full-time
yoga instructor and trainer.

37:00.734 --> 37:04.600
- Ashton.
- I don't have much regrets.

37:04.633 --> 37:07.133
Um, the accident was obviously
a big thing of my season.

37:07.166 --> 37:12.100
Um, I regret being, uh,
so unfocused at that point

37:12.133 --> 37:13.934
and allowing that
to happen to me.

37:13.967 --> 37:16.100
Um, but in the same breath,
I'm glad that it happened,

37:16.133 --> 37:17.333
because I think
there's a lot of learning

37:17.367 --> 37:19.467
that would have come from
that situation.

37:19.500 --> 37:21.266
Uh, what I'm currently do is

37:21.300 --> 37:24.834
I'm working for a family
in Atlanta, Georgia.

37:24.867 --> 37:26.066
I'm their private trainer.

37:26.100 --> 37:27.367
I do some security work
for them.

37:27.400 --> 37:29.700
I manage their estates.
- Ross.

37:29.734 --> 37:32.767
- I suppose trying to maybe
kiss everyone,

37:32.800 --> 37:34.300
and not being able to call--

37:34.333 --> 37:37.300
or recall those moments,
or remember those moments,
sorry.

37:37.333 --> 37:39.500
Um, I'm in Florida
at the moment, um,

37:39.533 --> 37:42.100
just spending time with my kid.
Trying to be a super dad.

37:42.133 --> 37:43.700
- Captain Lee.

37:43.734 --> 37:48.433
- I think my biggest regret
this season was the way I, uh,

37:48.467 --> 37:51.934
handled the situation
with Kate and, uh, Caroline.

37:51.967 --> 37:54.166
They still weren't
running boats.

37:54.200 --> 37:56.700
Probably will be
for a long time.
- Yeah.

37:56.734 --> 37:59.867
Now we are gonna take a look at
the scariest moment

37:59.900 --> 38:03.467
in "Below Deck" history.
Ashton's accident.

38:03.500 --> 38:06.166
Watch.

38:06.200 --> 38:07.767
- 'Kay, watch the lines,
watch the lines.

38:07.800 --> 38:09.033
Careful.
Oh, (BLEEP)!

38:09.066 --> 38:11.467
(BLEEP).

38:11.500 --> 38:13.467
- Man overboard.
- Take it off now.

38:13.500 --> 38:15.467
[screaming]
- Jesus Christ!

38:15.500 --> 38:18.867
- Ashton steps on the line.
And pulled him off the boat.

38:18.900 --> 38:22.000
Thank God for Brent,
the camera guy.

38:22.033 --> 38:25.033
Ashton owes Brent his life.

38:25.066 --> 38:26.500
- Just puts life
into perspective.

38:26.533 --> 38:28.367
It's like, one minute,
you're here.

38:28.400 --> 38:30.133
One minute, you're gone.
- Are you okay?

38:30.166 --> 38:31.633
- Get his ass on board.

38:31.667 --> 38:34.300
We were within 30 seconds
of him dying.

38:34.333 --> 38:36.367
I don't know
how I'd deal with that.

38:36.400 --> 38:38.467
I need a minute.

38:38.500 --> 38:41.600
- I've been given
a second chance here.

38:45.000 --> 38:47.800
- Well, I have a surprise
for you guys.

38:47.834 --> 38:51.533
Uh, please welcome the cameraman
who saved Ashton's life.

38:51.567 --> 38:55.834
Brent Freeburg is here.
[cheers and applause]

38:55.867 --> 38:58.734
- Hey, man.
- What's up, bro?

38:58.767 --> 39:01.500
- How are ya?
- I'm good, thanks to you.

39:01.533 --> 39:04.233
- Look at that handsome foot.
- It's good looking, right?

39:04.266 --> 39:05.433
- Hey, Brent.
- Hello.

39:05.467 --> 39:07.300
- How are you doing?
- I'm good.

39:07.333 --> 39:09.800
Hi, everybody.
- It's so great to meet you.

39:09.834 --> 39:11.767
First of all, this is
the first time the two of you

39:11.800 --> 39:14.100
have seen each other
since the show wrapped, right?

39:14.133 --> 39:15.200
- Yeah. Yeah.

39:15.233 --> 39:17.800
- Is there-is there anything
you wanna say to him?

39:17.834 --> 39:22.467
- Uh, just--
I mean, it's overwhelming.

39:22.500 --> 39:24.166
- It sure is.
- Um, you know, it's--

39:24.200 --> 39:27.133
this whole rewatching everything
has been

39:27.166 --> 39:30.800
extremely overwhelming for me
to have to relive that moment.

39:30.834 --> 39:32.467
I've really reflected
on the situation.

39:32.500 --> 39:34.667
Everything that I've done
up until now,

39:34.700 --> 39:36.967
and everything I've managed
to keep doing in my life

39:37.000 --> 39:38.333
is because of this man
sitting here.

39:38.367 --> 39:40.867
And it's--
what do you say to somebody?

39:40.900 --> 39:43.066
You know, like,
he is my real life hero.

39:43.100 --> 39:44.033
He really is.

39:44.066 --> 39:46.433
I hope that I can do something
with my life

39:46.467 --> 39:47.767
that will make him proud
one day.

39:47.800 --> 39:50.300
That he can say, you know,
"Thank God
I saved that guy's life

39:50.333 --> 39:53.400
"because look what
he's doing with himself."

39:53.433 --> 39:56.800
- That's nice.
- Thank you.

39:56.834 --> 39:58.467
- Tell me what happened
that day, Brent.

39:58.500 --> 40:00.133
- Well, I would say
that it wasn't just me.

40:00.166 --> 40:01.767
I've been getting
a lot of attention for sure.

40:01.800 --> 40:05.333
Um, but it was Rhylee who made
the first call to Captain.

40:05.367 --> 40:07.433
Captain took the boat
out of gear.

40:07.467 --> 40:09.300
Ross, who helped
untie the lines.

40:09.333 --> 40:11.066
And so, it was really
collectively all of us

40:11.100 --> 40:12.867
that came together,
you know.

40:12.900 --> 40:15.467
- But you're here
not to work on the boat.

40:15.500 --> 40:17.500
You're here shooting a TV show.

40:17.533 --> 40:19.333
So you're standing there
shooting this,

40:19.367 --> 40:21.567
and at some point,
you make the call,

40:21.600 --> 40:23.200
I gotta put my camera down.

40:23.233 --> 40:25.567
- Ross was working on-on
doing a cot line

40:25.600 --> 40:26.834
on one of the fenders behind me.

40:26.867 --> 40:30.266
And I noticed that Rhylee and
Ashton were down on the deck.

40:30.300 --> 40:33.600
On the swim deck.
And I just saw him go in.

40:33.633 --> 40:37.100
And, um, so I immediately
went down there.

40:37.133 --> 40:41.200
And then... basically assessed
the situation in the moment.

40:41.233 --> 40:43.100
You know, how do we
get these ropes off?

40:43.133 --> 40:44.400
Like, do I dive in?

40:44.433 --> 40:47.066
Does somebody dive in and go,
like, try to, like, unhook him?

40:47.100 --> 40:48.734
No, that's not gonna work.

40:48.767 --> 40:50.667
Is there a knife?
No.

40:50.700 --> 40:52.300
So, I just looked at the cleats

40:52.333 --> 40:53.900
and I realized that
that was the solution.

40:53.934 --> 40:55.166
And then started doing that.

40:55.200 --> 40:56.967
And I think Ross had come down
at that point

40:57.000 --> 40:58.467
and was just like,
"Get these lines off."

40:58.500 --> 41:01.700
And then after we got 'em off,
pick up the camera

41:01.734 --> 41:03.100
and then start shooting again.

41:03.133 --> 41:06.467
- So, what--
how long was all that?

41:06.500 --> 41:08.367
- I think--
- 15 seconds.

41:08.400 --> 41:10.233
- No, it was longer.
- It was actually longer.

41:10.266 --> 41:11.667
- He was in the water,
under the water,

41:11.700 --> 41:13.667
for maybe 25 seconds, I bet.

41:13.700 --> 41:15.834
Just struggling himself,
trying to get untied.

41:15.867 --> 41:18.433
- I-I had got to that point
where I had mentally prepared

41:18.467 --> 41:20.300
that my foot
was gonna be ripped off.

41:20.333 --> 41:23.700
That-that's the force that
was already around my ankle.

41:23.734 --> 41:25.900
You were--
if there was two seconds longer,

41:25.934 --> 41:29.133
my foot was-was ripped off.
- Wow.

41:29.166 --> 41:30.834
Makes you emotional
to hear about.

41:30.867 --> 41:32.800
- Yeah, every time
I tell the story,

41:32.834 --> 41:34.800
I get all super anxious.
I mean--

41:34.834 --> 41:37.233
- Well, if-if Rhylee
hadn't said "man overboard"

41:37.266 --> 41:39.467
in that instance,
it was all over.

41:39.500 --> 41:46.300
- Lee, you have, uh, been in
this industry for how long?

41:46.333 --> 41:47.400
- 35 years.

41:47.433 --> 41:50.033
- And this accident rates
where in the 35 years?

41:50.066 --> 41:51.600
- At the top.
- At the top.

41:51.633 --> 41:53.133
- At the top.
- What do you wanna say?

41:53.166 --> 41:57.500
- It never-- it's never, ever
happened in my career before.

41:57.533 --> 42:00.500
And, hopefully,
it will never happen again.

42:00.533 --> 42:04.300
- What do you wanna say to him?

42:04.333 --> 42:07.567
- Like I've always told him
before, he's a stud.

42:07.600 --> 42:10.433
- You're the real stud
of the sea, Captain Lee.

42:10.467 --> 42:13.767
- Come here, buddy.

42:19.867 --> 42:24.500
- Ashton, how-how
did this change you?

42:24.533 --> 42:27.300
- It was a massive wakeup call.

42:27.333 --> 42:30.100
Um, I think you get complacent.

42:30.133 --> 42:31.867
You start forgetting things
on deck.

42:31.900 --> 42:35.600
Um, it's a dangerous job we do.

42:35.633 --> 42:38.900
Um, and I think it was just
a massive wakeup call.

42:38.934 --> 42:41.967
- Um, I'm so glad
you-you joined us.

42:42.000 --> 42:43.734
I know you're pretty, uh--

42:43.767 --> 42:47.233
from what I understand,
you like to stay
behind the scenes.

42:47.266 --> 42:49.000
- There's a reason
that I be behind the camera.

42:49.033 --> 42:50.500
- Yes.
[laughter]

42:50.533 --> 42:53.333
And this wasn't your choice,
your first choice to be here.

42:53.367 --> 42:55.400
But we begged you
and begged you.

42:55.433 --> 42:58.133
So, it's--
we're all so happy to see you.

42:58.166 --> 42:59.166
- I'm happy to be here.

42:59.200 --> 43:01.166
- Thanks for a great
charter season, everybody.

43:01.200 --> 43:03.266
See ya next time.

43:03.300 --> 43:10.433
♪♪♪
